I"‚ï<h2 id="motivation">Motivation</h2>

<p>Covid-19 - the bug that won‚Äôt go away. It‚Äôs hard to believe we‚Äôve been here for over 2 years. Perhaps like you, I went from checking the Epi curves daily back in 2019, to loneliness and pandemic fatigue, to baking sourdough and planting stuff, to kind of, sort of, almost going back to normal. And then‚Ä¶ Omicron. So here we are, back in the familiar bubble.</p>

<p>Speaking of Epi curves, it‚Äôs very easy to make one of your own - certainly easier than sourdough starter. Here‚Äôs one using <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ggplot2</code> and the Covid-19 global dataset maintained by <a href="https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus-source-data">Our World in Data, OWID</a>. OWID compiles this dataset from several sources including the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins University, national government reports, and the Human Mortality Database (2021).</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-r" data-lang="r"><span class="n">library</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">tidyverse</span><span class="p">)</span></code></pre></figure>

<h2 id="data-preparation">Data Preparation</h2>

<p>First, let‚Äôs import and examine the .csv from the ‚ÄúOur World in Data‚Äù Github <a href="https://github.com/owid/covid-19-data/tree/master/public/data">repo</a>.</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-r" data-lang="r"><span class="n">raw_data</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">read.csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"../data/epi_curves/owid-covid-data.csv"</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w">
